T1  - Multilateral tariff cooperation during the formation of customs unions
AU  - Bagwell, Kyle
AU  - Staiger, Robert W.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 42
IS  - 1
SP  - 91
EP  - 123
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(96)01443-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199696014432
KW  - Customs unions
KW  - Preferential agreements
KW  - The Multilateral Trading System
AB  - We study the implications of customs-union formation for multilateral tariff cooperation. We model cooperation in multilateral trade policy as self-enforcing, in that it involves balancing the current gains from deviating unilaterally from an agreed-upon trade policy against the future losses from forfeiting the benefits of multilateral cooperation that such a unilateral defection would imply. The early stages of the process of customs-union formation are shown to alter this dynamic incentive constraint in a way that leads to a temporary “honeymoon” for liberal multilateral trade policies. We find, however, that the harmony between customs unions and multilateral liberalization is temporary: eventually, as the full impact of the emerging customs union becomes felt, a less favorable balance between current and future conditions re-emerges, and the liberal multilateral policies of the honeymoon phase cannot be sustained.
ER  - 

